post_text: We have been transparent with you throughout this process. The plan was to hold a graduation with social distancing in place and we released that information earlier this week. That plan had to change when we received the information below. This applies to all schools across the State of Ohio. We are a government entity and abide by the the recommendations set forth from the Department of Education and the Governor’s office. If that advisement changes, then of course, we would reassess. That is not the current reality of the situation. We can’t stress enough that the pandemic has impacted every single person in some way. Everyone is disappointed.

post_text: School Districts in Ohio have been advised by the State Board of Education and the Governor’s office that we should refrain from holding any in person ceremonies to close the school year. That would include graduation and prom. The recommendation is to hold a virtual ceremony. That is what we will plan on doing moving forward, adhering to our original graduation date. Please view this video from Principal Shutler and share ideas that you would like to see included in the virtual ceremony. We know that this is far from ideal, but we cannot choose our circumstances, only how we respond. Please keep your suggestions and comments constructive and solution oriented. We want to show our class of 2020 the recognition they deserve.
text: School Districts in Ohio have been advised by the State Board of Education and the Governor’s office that we should refrain from holding any in person ceremonies to close the school year. That would include graduation and prom. The recommendation is to hold a virtual ceremony. That is what we will plan on doing moving forward, adhering to our original graduation date. Please view this video from Principal Shutler and share ideas that you would like to see included in the virtual ceremony. We know that this is far from ideal, but we cannot choose our circumstances, only how we respond. Please keep your suggestions and comments constructive and solution oriented. We want to show our class of 2020 the recognition they deserve.

Ohio Schools to Recognize School Bus Safety Week

Ohio schools will soon be recognizing the importance that schools buses and their drivers play in transporting more than 800,000 Ohio students to and from schools during National School Bus Safety Week, Oct. 21 through 25.
The Ohio School Boards Association emphasized the importance of safety both on and off schools buses in a press release Thursday.
"We train our bus drivers to be cautious, but we need help from the community when motorists are driving around school buses and in school zones," Ohio School Boards Association (OSBA) Senior Transportation Consultant Pete Japikse said. "We need to prevent students from being struck and harmed… More

post_text:
The ULMS 7th Grade Career/Computer class as well as the 7th Grade AE had the opportunity to visit IEBW (Electricians-apprenticeship training facility in Wheeling.)

Doug Giffin - IEBW President - gave a detailed presentation on the Electricians trades and apprenticeship program that is offered for our area. He furthermore explained the current trade/skilled labor needs with the influx of local work available. He went on to show the students some of the tools and equipment that electricians work with on a daily basis.

Our day trip concluded with a short stop at Schumacher Homes. The staff welcomed our students and explained how each house constructed takes about 4 months to complete. More importantly, the job can require up to 23 different skilled-trades craftsman to complete it. (Carpenters, bricklayers, drywallers, electricians, glazers, tilers, etc...).

Lastly, we explained with a solid and successful career choice; could ultimately lead to re-visiting Schumacher Homes; becoming a homeowner. (Goals that many students have written about in their Life Goals activity.

post_text:
THANK YOU AGAIN UNION LOCAL and ST CLAIRSVILLE FOR ANOTHER SUCCESSFUL“Battle for a Cure”challenge !!!!
You all continually cease to amaze me!!!!
This battle also known as the “Pink War”.. was a four day challenge within our schools this week to see who could raise the most money for cancer.
We are happy to announce that collectively both schools raised a total of $9250.70 !!!

During tonight‘s halftime the special design “Pink War” trophy was awarded to Union local for raising the most money!
Union local raised $7250.70 with Saint Clairsville’s $2000... Our SUPER Superintendent Mr. Ben Porter accepted the trophy for this challenge on our behalf.
Way to go Jets!!!

We would like to thank both districts especially Mr. Skaggs and his team for making such a fantastic difference in the lives of our local family and friends who are battling this life threatening/ altering disease!!!

You are all winners and have fantastic hearts for the needs of others and we thank you all!!!☺️☺️👏🏻👏🏻

This Friday, August 23, there is no football game, so the Union Local Soccer Team would like to invite the HS student body to attend their home game against Magnolia. Kickoff is at 5:30. There will be FREE ADMISSION for all HS students, as well as free hot dogs and drinks! The Jets Marching Band will be there playing pregame and at halftime, we will have a kick contest where the winner will get a free athletic pass good for all Jets games for the 2019-2020 school year! Raffles and other prizes will also be given away! Hope to see a large crowd supporting our soccer players and enjoying this FREE night of fun!

post_text:
Hope everyone is enjoying their summer!
Just a few announcements for the upcoming month .........
1. We are transitioning from the One Call Now to a new call system which will be in operation for the new school year , we will keep you posted on this .
2. Back to school Fair is being planned for Friday Aug 16th @ 6-8pm in MS courtyard . We will give more info as date approaches.
3. We are now accepting clothing donations for the clothes closet which will be set up in the MS Gym Aug 16 during the back to school fair .
*****DONATIONS FOR THE CLOTHES CLOSET CAN BE DROPPED OFF AT THE HIGH SCHOOL ENTRANCE UNTIL AUG 10TH . If no one answers door just leave your donation by the door it will be checked daily .
Enjoy the rest of summer break and check back soon for updates !
